text: Alopecia Mental Retardation Syndrome 3 (AMRSD3) is a genetic disorder characterized by hair loss and intellectual disability. It is caused by mutations in the TBX1 gene, which are passed down through families. The condition affects both males and females equally, and it can lead to significant physical and developmental issues throughout a person's life. Treatment options for AMRSD3 are limited, but supportive care and early intervention can help manage the symptoms and improve quality of life.

Amed syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects children, characterized by global developmental delay with impaired intellectual development, onset of bone marrow failure and myelodysplastic syndrome in childhood, and poor overall growth with short stature. It is caused by mutations in the ADH5 gene located on chromosome 4q, which is accompanied by a specific homozygous or heterozygous allele in the ALDH2 gene (E504K) on chromosome 12q24. Both of these genes are necessary for the disorder to manifest, consistent with digenic inheritance. The exact synonym of Amed syndrome is AMEDS.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1j is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the tooth enamel. It is characterized by defective formation and hardening of the enamel, which can lead to chipping, cracking, and sensitivity. This condition is caused by mutations in the ACPT gene, which is located on chromosome 19q13. Amelogenesis imperfecta type 1j shares some similarities with other types of amelogenesis imperfecta, but has a unique genetic basis.

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita (AMC) is a type of autosomal recessive disorder that affects the musculoskeletal system. It is characterized by the development of multiple joint contractures, which are fixed joint deformities, in two or more body regions before birth. AMC can be caused by abnormalities in fetal development or birth, and it has a strong genetic component. The severity of AMC varies greatly among affected individuals, with some people having mild symptoms while others may have severe and disabling conditions. Treatment for AMC depends on the specific symptoms and can include physical therapy, joint manipulation, or surgery.

childhood embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes c19mc altered is a type of childhood onset.
childhood embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes c19mc altered has definition A childhood embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes, C19MC-altered that arises from the supratentorial brain and occurs in children..

Primary hypoalphalipoproteinemia 1 is a type of hypolipoproteinemia characterized by low levels of high-density lipoprotein (HDL) in the blood. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ABC1 gene on chromosome 9q31, which also causes mutations in Tangier disease. This condition is also known as familial HDL deficiency or familial hypoalphalipoproteinemia.

Primary hypoalphalipoproteinemia 2 is a type of hypolipoproteinemia characterized by dysfunctional apoA-I production, resulting in undetectable levels of apoA-I in serum and in markedly low levels of serum high density lipoprotein cholesterol. It is generally an autosomal recessive disorder associated with extensive atherosclerosis, xanthomas, and corneal opacities. The condition has a material basis in homozygous, compound heterozygous, or heterozygous mutation in the APOA1 gene on chromosome 11q23. It has an exact synonym of Apolipoprotein A-I deficiency.

Arrhythmogenic right ventricular dysplasia 14 (ARVD-14) is a type of arrhythmogenic right ventricular cardiomyopathy. It is an autosomal dominant disease that affects the heart muscle. ARVD-14 has a material basis in some cases and is characterized by palpitations, chest pain, and presyncope. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the CDH2 gene located on chromosome 18q12.

Amelogenesis imperfecta type 2a6 is a genetic disorder that affects the enamel formation process. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the faulty gene (one from each parent) to develop the condition. The gene responsible for this disorder is located on chromosome 14q32 and codes for a protein called GPR68.
Hypomineralization, or insufficient mineralization of enamel, is one of the main features of Amelogenesis imperfecta type 2a6. This can result in enamel that is thinner than normal and has a mottled appearance. Additionally, there may be other defects in enamel formation, such as hypocalcification or failure to form proper enamel layers.
Overall, Amelogenesis imperfecta type 2a6 can lead to disrupted teeth and an increased risk of cavities and other dental problems. Treatment options may include fluoride therapy, dental bonding, or orthodontic treatment to address any cosmetic or structural issues.

Anauxetic dysplasia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is a spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, which means that it affects the development of the bones in the spine and extremities. The condition has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the POP1 gene on chromosome 8q22.

Anauxetic dysplasia 3, also known as anauxetic spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, is a rare genetic disorder that affects bone growth and development. It is characterized by severe short stature, brachydactyly (short fingers and toes), skin laxity, joint hypermobility, and a high frequency of joint dislocations. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a child must inherit two copies of the gene for the disease to develop. It is caused by mutations in the NEPRO gene, which is located on chromosome 3q13.
intracranial berry aneurysm 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

intracranial berry aneurysm 2 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm.
intracranial berry aneurysm 2 has the definition "An intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death and has been mapped to chromosome 19q13.".
intracranial berry aneurysm 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 4 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is a sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This can lead to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, which is a sudden-onset disease that can cause severe disability and death. It has been mapped to chromosome 5p15.2-p14.3.

intracranial berry aneurysm 5 is a type of intracranial aneurysm that has the potential to rupture and cause a subarachnoid hemorrhage. This type of aneurism is characterized by an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, which can lead to severe disability and death if it ruptures. It has been mapped to chromosome Xp22.

An intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death and has been mapped to chromosome 9p21.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 7 is a specific type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This can lead to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can result in severe disability and death. It has been mapped to chromosome 11q24-q25.

An intracranial berry aneurysm 8 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that has the potential to rupture and cause a subarachnoid hemorrhage, which can lead to severe disability and death. It is characterized by an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, and has been mapped to chromosome 14q23.

Intracranial berry aneurysm 9 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm. Intracranial berry aneurysm 9 has the definition "An intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can lead to severe disability and death and has been mapped to chromosome 2q33.1.".

Yes, intracranial berry aneurysm 10 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm. This can lead to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, which can cause severe disability and death if not treated promptly. It has been mapped to chromosome 8q12.1.

intracranial berry aneurysm 11 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, an outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery, which leads to a subarachnoid hemorrhage. This type of intracranial berry aneurysm is mapped to chromosome 8p22 and can lead to severe disability and death if left untreated.

intracranial berry aneurysm 12 is a type of intracranial berry aneurysm that is characterized by the rupture of an intracranial aneurysm, which is a outpouching or sac-like widening of a cerebral artery. This can lead to a subarachnoid hemorrhage, a sudden-onset disease that can be severe and life-threatening. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the THSD1 gene on chromosome 13q14.

acute myeloid leukemia with bcr abl1 is a type of acute myeloid leukemia characterized by the presence of blasts that harbor BCR-ABL1 translocation in the absence of a history and clinical and laboratory features of chronic myelogenous leukemia. It is also known as Acute myeleoid leukemia with BCR-ABL1.

User, it seems that you have provided information about aortic valve disease 3. Aortic valve disease 3 is indeed related to bicuspid aortic valve disease and can be associated with other conditions such as aneurysm of the aortic root and ascending aorta in some patients. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the ROBO4 gene on chromosome 11q24.

arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 1 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, which is characterized by the congenital contracture of multiple joints. It is caused by mutations in the LGI4 gene on chromosome 19q13.

Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 3 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita that is characterized by decreased fetal movements, hypotonia, variable skeletal defects, including clubfoot and scoliosis, and delayed motor milestones with difficulty walking. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SYNE1 gene on chromosome 6q25.

arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 4 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, which is a condition characterized by multiple joint contractures. It can also be caused by homozygous mutation in the SCYL2 gene on chromosome 12q23. The condition has been given the name "Zain syndrome."
Arthrogryposis multiplex congenita 5 is a type of arthrogryposis multiplex congenita that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the TOR1A gene on chromosome 9q34.

X-linked mental retardation hypotonic facies syndrome 1 is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability. It is characterized primarily by severe mental retardation, dysmorphic facies, and a highly skewed X-inactivation pattern in carrier women. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the ATRX gene. This syndrome comprises several previously reported separate syndromes including Carpenter-Waziri, Holmes-Gang, and Smith-Fineman-Myers syndromes. X-linked alpha-thalassemia/mental retardation syndrome is an allelic disorder with a similar phenotype but also includes Hb H inclusion bodies in erythrocytes.

x linked intellectual developmental disorder 109 is a type of syndromic x linked intellectual disability.
x linked intellectual developmental disorder 109 has definition A syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by mildly to moderately impaired intellectual development associated with learning difficulties, communication deficits, attention problems, hyperactivity, and autistic behavior and that has material basis in disruption of the FMR2 gene (AFF2), either by expansion of a CCG repeat in the 5-prime untranslated region or by deletion.
x linked intellectual developmental disorder 109 also has exact synonym Fragile XE syndrome, and fragile site on chromosome Xq28.

Syndromic X-linked intellectual disorder, also known as Lujan-Fryns syndrome, is a type of intellectual disability that is characterized by a tall stature, distinct facial dysmorphism, and behavioral problems. It is caused by mutations in the MED12 gene on chromosome Xq13. Syndromic X-linked intellectual disorders are a group of genetic conditions where intellectual disability is one of the main features, along with other physical or developmental abnormalities. These syndromes can be caused by mutations in a single gene or multiple genes and they often have a strong inheritance pattern, either being inherited from one's mother (X-linked recessive) or both parents (X-linked dominant). Opitz-Kaveggia syndrome is an allelic disorder with an overlapping phenotype.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome, Periodontal Type 1 (EDSPT1) is a subtype of the Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes (EDS), which are genetic disorders affecting connective tissue in the body. EDSPT1 is characterized by severe periodontal inflammation and has a material basis in heterozygous mutations in the C1R gene on chromosome 12p13. It is also associated with other EDS-related symptoms, such as hyperextensible skin, joint hypermobility, and widened atrophic scars.

Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome (EDS) is a group of genetic disorders that affect connective tissue in the body. EDS can cause problems with joints, bones, blood vessels, and skin. There are several types of EDS, including Periodontal Type 2, which affects the gums and jawbones. This type is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the gene, there's a 50% chance that their child will inherit it.

Pretibial dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa is a type of epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica.
Epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica is a group of genodermatric disorders characterized by recurrent blistering and scarring, mainly in the pretibial area. Pretibial dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa has a definition as an epidermolysis bullosa dystrophica that is characterized by recurrent blistering and scarring, mainly in the pretibial area and that has_material_basis_in heterozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the type VII collagen gene (COL7A1) on chromosome 3p21. The lesions often show lichenoid features. Pretibial dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa is allelic to autosomal dominant and recessive dystrophic epidermolysis bullosa.

King-Denborough syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the muscles. It is characterized by distinctive facial features, such as downslanted palpebral fissures, widely spaced eyes, epicanthal folds, and low-set ears. Other features may include malar hypoplasia, micrognathia, high-arched palate, clinodactyly, single palmar crease, pectus excavatum, winging of the scapulae, lumbar lordosis, and mild thoracic scoliosis. Pathogenic variants in RYR1 have been found in some individuals with King-Denborough syndrome.

Congenital myopathy 1b, also known as multiminicore disease, is a type of congenital myopathy characterized by multiple areas of reduced mitochondrial oxidative activity running along a limited extent of the longitudinal axis of the muscle fiber. It is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the RYR1 gene on chromosome 19q13. The disease can be classified into four groups: classic form, moderate form with hand involvement, antenatal form with arthrogryposis multiplex congenita, and ophthalmoplegic form.

Rhabdomyolysis myalgia syndrome (RMS) is a type of myopathy characterized by muscle breakdown, heat and exertion-related muscle pain, cramping symptoms, severe muscle pain, sudden elevation and subsequent fall of serum creatine phosphokinase levels, and products of muscle breakdown in the urine. It is associated with variations in the RYR1 gene. RMS can be caused by a range of external triggers, including strenuous exercise beyond one's limit of fatigue, heat stress, illicit drug or alcohol abuse, use of supplements or certain medications, recent viral illness or muscle trauma.

Autoimmune epilepsy is a type of autoimmune disease that affects the central nervous system. It is characterized by new-onset refractory seizures along with subacute progressive cognitive decline and behavioral or psychiatric dysfunction, and is associated with abnormal immunoglobulin levels.

tuberculous encephalopathy is a type of tuberculosis that affects the brain and spinal cord. It is characterized by inflammation, edema, and damage to the central nervous system. Symptoms can include headache, fever, stiff neck, balance and coordination problems, seizures, and altered mental status or coma. Tuberculous encephalopathy is typically diagnosed with a combination of imaging studies, spinal tap, and laboratory tests. Treatment typically involves antibiotics, steroids, and supportive care.

Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) is a type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that affects the lymphatic system. It is characterized by the presence of abnormal large B cells, which are a type of white blood cell. There are several subtypes of DLBCL, including activated B-cell (ABC) type and germinal center B-cell (GCB) type. The ABC type is further divided into two subcategories: DLBCL activated B-cell type and DLBCL unclassified.
DLBCL activated B-cell type is a type of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma that is characterized by the expression of certain genes, including CD44, PKCbeta1, Cyclin D2, BCL-2, and IRF4/MUM1. It is considered to be an aggressive subtype of DLBCL.
In summary, diffuse large B-cell lymphoma activated B cell type is a subcategory of diffuse large B-cell lymphoma that is characterized by the expression of certain genes and is considered to be an aggressive form of the disease.

Diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL) is a type of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that arises from B cells. It is characterized by the presence of large, neoplastic cells in the lymph nodes and other organs. DLBCL can be classified into two main types: germinal center B cell type and activated B cell type. The germinal center B cell type is further subdivided into four subtypes: GCB1, GCB2, IGHV-mutated, and Not-IGHV-mutated. The activated B cell type is characterized by the expression of APRIL, BAFF-receptor, RELA, c-MYC, and IRF4 genes, as well as cyclin D1 overexpression. In addition to these main types, there are several other subtypes of DLBCL that have been identified, including those with unique gene expression profiles or histological features.

acute necrotizing pancreatitis is a type of acute pancreatitis characterized by one or more areas of necrosis in the pancreas with varying degree of involvement of the surrounding tissues or organ systems.
acute hemorrhagic pancreatitis is a type of acute pancreatitis characterized by the presence of acute inflammation, necrosis and hemorrhage in the pancreas.

Cowden syndrome type 4, also known as Cowden-Bazel syndrome, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the presence of multiple hamartomas (benign tumors) in various tissues and organs. It is caused by heterozygous germline hypermethylation of the KLLN gene on chromosome 10q23, resulting in a loss of function of the protein product of this gene. This leads to the development of characteristic features such as multiple hamartomas, skin tags, and an increased risk of malignancy. The syndrome can affect various organs including the gastrointestinal tract, breasts, genitourinary system, and endocrine glands. Treatment may involve surgery or other medical interventions to manage symptoms and reduce the risk of complications.

Cowden Syndrome 5, also known as Cowden Syndrome Type V, is a genetic disorder that is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the PIK3CA gene on chromosome 3q26. It is characterized by the presence of multiple hamartomas, which are benign tumors that can occur in various parts of the body, including the skin, gastrointestinal tract, and oral cavity. Additionally, individuals with Cowden Syndrome Type V may experience other symptoms such as acne-like eruptions, gingival hyperplasia, and an increased risk of certain types of cancer.

Cowden Syndrome 6, also known as Cowden Syndrome Type 6, is a distinct subtype of Cowden Syndrome characterized by the presence of a heterozygous mutation in the AKT1 gene located on chromosome 14q32.3. This genetic variation leads to the overproduction of proteins involved in cell growth and division, which can result in various symptoms such as facial asymmetry, breast lumps or tumors, and a higher risk of developing cancerous tumors throughout the body.

Cowden Syndrome 7, also known as Cowden Syndrome Type VII, is a genetic disorder characterized by the presence of multiple benign tumors in various organs and tissues. It is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the SEC23B gene on chromosome 20p11. The symptoms can include facial skin tags, acne-like eruptions, breast lumps, and multiple hamartomas. It's important to note that Cowden Syndrome is a rare disorder with an unknown prevalence. If you suspect you may have this condition or are concerned about your risk factors, it's important to speak with a healthcare provider for further evaluation and guidance.
High Grade B-Cell Lymphoma with MYC and BCL2 or BCL6 Rearrangements is a type of cancer that affects the white blood cells. It is also known as HGBL-DH/TH

Parsley is a popular herb used in various dishes and salads, but for some individuals, it can trigger allergic reactions. A parsley allergy is a type of vegetable allergy, which occurs when the immune system mistakenly identifies parsley as a harmful substance and responds by producing antibodies against it. Parsley allergy symptoms may include itching or swelling of the tongue, difficulty breathing, hives, and digestive problems such as diarrhea and abdominal pain. It is important to note that parsley allergy is relatively uncommon, but if you suspect you have a parsley allergy, it is best to avoid consuming it and speak with your healthcare provider about any necessary treatment or preventative measures.

Dill allergy is a specific type of vegetable allergy that occurs when the body's immune system mistakenly identifies dill as an invader and responds by producing antibodies against it. This can lead to symptoms such as itching, swelling, and difficulty breathing. Dill allergy is also known as Anethum graveolens allergy, which refers to the specific type of vegetable that causes the allergic reaction. It's important to note that while dill allergy is a relatively uncommon food allergy, it can still cause significant discomfort and health problems for those who suffer from it. If you think you may have a dill allergy, it's always best to consult with an allergist or other healthcare professional for proper diagnosis and treatment.

rnaset2 deficient cystic leukoencephalopathy is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the brain. It is characterized by non-progressive leukoencephalopathy, bilateral cysts in the anterior part of the temporal lobe, cerebral white matter anomalies and severe psychomotor impairment. The condition has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance, but it is not clear if this is a common form of leukoencephalopathy or just an unusual one that happens to have this particular combination of symptoms.

Bardet-Biedl syndrome (also known as BBS) is a genetic disorder characterized by various physical and developmental abnormalities. It can be caused by mutations in one of several different genes, with the IFT172 gene being one such example. The specific symptoms and severity of BBS can vary widely depending on which genes are affected and the individual's unique genetic makeup.

Bardet-Biedl syndrome type 20 (also known as BBS20) is a specific subtype of BBS characterized by certain common features such as rod-cone dystrophy, postaxial polydactyly, truncal obesity, renal anomalies, and learning disability. Additionally, it has been associated with hypogonadism in males and genital abnormalities in females. As with all forms of BBS, the exact cause is not yet fully understood, but research continues to shed light on this complex condition.

Bardet-Biedl Syndrome Type 21, also known as BBS-21, is a genetic disorder that affects various organ systems in the body. It is caused by mutations in the C8ORF37 gene on chromosome 8q22. This condition is characterized by obesity, postaxial polydactyly (an extra finger or toe on the back of the hand or foot), retinal degeneration, and mild cognitive impairment. BBS-21 is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that to develop the condition, a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent.

Bardet-Biedl syndrome (BBS) is a genetic disorder characterized by a variety of physical and developmental abnormalities. BBS 22, also known as Bardet-Biedl syndrome type 22 or BBSR, is one specific subtype of BBS that is caused by mutations in the IFT74 gene on chromosome 9p21. It is characterized by retinitis pigmentosa, obesity, polydactyly (too many fingers or toes), hypogonadism (underactive reproductive glands), and intellectual disability. The syndrome has a material basis in compound heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the IFT74 gene and is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner.

Critical COVID-19 refers to a severe case of the virus that can lead to life-threatening complications. It is characterized by acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS), sepsis, septic shock, or other conditions that require life sustaining therapies such as mechanical ventilation or vasopressor therapy.

The definition of severe COVID-19 as provided by the user is accurate. It outlines three criteria that must be met for a case of COVID-19 to be considered severe: oxygen saturation levels below 90% on room air, respiratory rate above 30 breaths/min in adults and children over 5 years old, and the presence of signs of severe respiratory distress. These criteria are used by healthcare professionals to determine if a patient has severe COVID-19, which requires different treatment strategies than mild or asymptomatic cases. It is important for individuals who suspect they have been exposed to COVID-19 to seek medical attention promptly and follow all recommended guidelines for self-isolation and care.

That is correct. Non-severe COVID-19 is a type of the virus that does not present with severe or critical symptoms, as defined by certain criteria. These cases typically have milder symptoms and may require less medical intervention than those with severe or critical illnesses.
Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 2 is a type of congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles that has material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.
congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 2 is a type of disease where bilateral ptosis and restrictive ophthalmoplegia with the globes fixed in extreme abduction (exotropia) are present, and it has material basis in homozygous mutation in the ARIX gene on chromosome 11q13.
Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 3a is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 3c (CFEOM3c) is a genetic disorder that affects the muscles responsible for eye movement. It is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, which means that a person has a 50% chance of inheriting the condition if one of their parents passes it on. The specific cause of CFEOM3c is a reciprocal translocation between chromosomes 2 and 13, specifically at positions q37.3 and q12.11. This genetic abnormality leads to the formation of excess collagen in the extraocular muscles, causing them to become stiff and rigid. As a result, individuals with CFEOM3c may experience symptoms such as drooping eyelids (ptosis), limited upward eye movement (esotropia), and difficulty in fully opening their eyes (blepharoptosis). These symptoms can cause vision problems and other complications if left untreated.

Congenital fibrosis of the extraocular muscles 5 (CFEOM5) is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the extraocular muscles, specifically those responsible for moving the eyeballs. It is caused by mutations in the COL25A1 gene on chromosome 4q25. The condition can lead to various degrees of vision impairment and may also cause other ocular and systemic abnormalities.

Tukel syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the extraocular muscles, resulting in nonprogressive restrictive ophthalmoplegia with blepharoptosis of the right eye and postaxial oligodactyly/oligosyndactyly of the hands. The syndrome is characterized by the right eye being more severely affected than the left, and there is a material basis for it in some autosomal recessive inheritance.

Retinal cone dystrophy 3b, also known as cone dystrophy with supernormal rod responses, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects vision. It is characterized by onset in the first or second decade of life of very marked photophobia, myopia, reduced color vision along the red-green axis, central scotomata with peripheral widespread sensitivity loss predominating in the superior visual field and having a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the KCNV2 gene on chromosome 9p24.

Retinal cone dystrophy 4, also known as CACNA2D4-mediated retinal dystrophy, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by progressive degeneration of the photoreceptors in the retina. It is caused by mutations in the CACNA2D4 gene, which is located on chromosome 12p13. This condition primarily affects the cone cells of the retina, leading to vision loss and night blindness. There is currently no cure for Retinal cone dystrophy 4, but various treatment options may be available to manage its symptoms, such as low vision aids and genetic counseling.

Retinal Cone Dystrophy 1 (RCD1) is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by the gradual loss of function in cone photoreceptors, which are responsible for color vision. The inheritance pattern for RCD1 involves mutations in one of the two copies of the gene that encodes for the proteins involved in cone function. There is no known cure for this condition, but early detection and regular monitoring can help manage its symptoms.

Retinal Cone Dystrophy 3a, also known as RCD3a, is a type of cone dystrophy that affects an individual's ability to see. It is characterized by reduced visual acuity, night blindness, and abnormal color vision. The condition is caused by a mutation in the gene encoding the gamma subunit of cone cGMP-phosphodiesterase (PDE6H0), which is located on chromosome 12p13.

Benign peritoneal solitary fibrous tumor (BPSFT) is a type of benign neoplasm that occurs in the abdominal cavity, specifically on the peritoneum. It is characterized by the presence of prominent hemangiopericytoma-like vessels and is considered to be a low malignancy risk tumor.

Breast adenocarcinoma is a type of breast cancer that originates from the mammary gland's milk-producing ducts. It is characterized by the presence of malignant epithelial cells with abundant clear cytoplasm which contains glycogen, as seen in glycogen rich carcinoma.

central conducting lymphatic anomaly is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
central conducting lymphatic anomaly is a type of lymphatic system disease.
central conducting lymphatic anomaly is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
central conducting lymphatic anomaly has definition A lymphatic system disease that is characterized by dysfunction of the thoracic duct or cisterna chyli, leading to a retrograde flux of lymphatic fluid or abnormal drainage of lymphatic fluid and that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the EPHB4 gene on chromosome 7q22..
central conducting lymphatic anomaly has exact synonym lymphatic malformation-7.

Generalized lymphatic anomaly (GLA) is a congenital disorder characterized by the abnormal development of lymphatic vessels, leading to the formation of cysts and other malformations in various parts of the body, including the lungs, pleura, bones, and soft tissues. It is a type of lymphedema, which is a condition where excess fluid accumulates in the tissues due to damage or blockage of the lymphatic system. GLA can cause a variety of symptoms, such as swelling, pain, and limited mobility, and can be diagnosed through imaging studies and biopsies. Treatment options may include surgery, radiation therapy, and medications to manage symptoms.

glutatione synthetase deficiency with 5 oxoprolinuria is a type of glutathione synthetase deficiency.
glutathione synthetase deficiency is a disorder that results from the defective activity of glutathione synthetase enzyme, which leads to a decrease in the level of glutathione in the body and an increase in the levels of gamma-glutamylcysteine and 5-oxoproline.

Mixed phenotype acute leukemia with MLL rearranged is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia. It is characterized by blasts that carry a translocation between the MLL (KMT2A) gene at 11q23.3 and another gene partner. This condition has also been referred to as mixed phenotype acute leukemia with t(v;11q23.3); MLL rearranged.

That's correct! Mixed phenotype acute leukemia b myeloid, also known as ABL1 with e1a-e19q, is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia that has blasts with expression of B-lymphoid and myeloid lineage markers but is negative for MLL translocation and t(9;22)(q34;q11.2) translocation.

Mixed phenotype acute leukemia (MPAL) is a type of acute biphenotypic leukemia. It is characterized by the presence of blasts that express antigens of both T and myeloid lineages, which makes it distinct from other forms of acute leukemia that are restricted to either T or myeloid cells. The classification of MPAL depends on the percentage of blasts in the bone marrow and the level of expression of the relevant surface markers. It is important to note that while MPAL has a higher risk of relapse than other types of acute leukemia, it generally has a better prognosis when treated with intensive chemotherapy and stem cell transplantation compared to other types of biphenotypic leukemia.

B cell prolymphocytic leukemia is a type of cancer that affects the blood and bone marrow. It is characterized by an abnormal increase in immature B cells, which are white blood cells that play a role in fighting off infections. This type of leukemia is also known as prolymphocytic leukemia, B-cell type or simply B cell leukemia.

Prolymphocytic leukemia, T-cell type is a rare form of leukemia characterized by the excessive proliferation of mature T cells in the blood and bone marrow. It affects both children and adults but is more common in children. The symptoms may include fever, fatigue, bruising or bleeding, weight loss, and frequent infections. Treatment typically involves chemotherapy, radiation therapy, stem cell transplantation, and targeted therapies.

Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome (X-linked) is a type of Fetal akinesia deformation sequence syndrome. It is an X-linked monogenic disease that is characterized by brain malformations, telecanthus (a condition where the eyes point upwards), and narrow palpebral fissures (the space between the eyebrows).

Frontonasal dysplasia is a type of craniosynostosis, which occurs when one or more of the joints between the skull bones close too early. This can lead to abnormal development of the forehead and midface, as well as other facial features. Mandibuloacral dysplasia is a condition characterized by underdevelopment of the lower jaw and collarbone, bone loss at the ends of the fingers and toes, skin degeneration, and partial lipodystrophy.

Overall, Antley-Bixler syndrome is a complex disorder that requires careful diagnosis and management by a team of medical professionals, including genetic counselors, endocrinologists, orthopedic surgeons, and other specialists.

Chronic traumatic encephalopathy (CTE) is a type of tauopathy that is characterized by an abundance of hyperphosphorylated tau protein in neurons, astrocytes and cell processes around blood vessels and that is associated with repetitive head impacts or exposure to blast waves.

Traumatic brain injury (TBI) is a type of acquired brain injury that occurs as a result of a sudden trauma to the head or a violent impact. It can cause damage to the brain tissue and can lead to long-term or even permanent disabilities, depending on the severity of the injury. TBI can be caused by various means such as falls, car accidents, sports injuries, or military combat situations. It is important for individuals who have experienced a TBI to receive proper medical attention and rehabilitation in order to maximize their recovery potential.

Salivary gland mucoepidermoid carcinoma is a type of salivary gland cancer that occurs in the epithelial cells of the salivary glands. It is characterized by its location in the salivary gland and its resemblance to other types of mucin-producing tumors, such as mammary analog secretory carcinoma and bronchioloalveolar carcinoma. This type of cancer can be treated with surgery or radiation therapy, depending on the stage and location of the tumor.

Neuronal intranuclear inclusion disease is a type of autosomal dominant neurodegenerative disease that has a material basis in trinucleotide repeat expansion. It is characterized by a wide range of clinical manifestations, including pyramidal and extrapyramidal symptoms, cerebellar ataxia, cognitive decline and dementia, peripheral neuropathy, and autonomic dysfunction. The disease has a genetic basis and is caused by an expansion of trinucleotide repeats in the 5-prime untranslated region of the NOTCH2NLC gene on chromosome 1q21.

Essential tremor 6 (ET6) is a type of autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by adult-onset kinetic and/or postural tremors affecting the upper limbs. These tremors are caused by trinucleotide repeat expansion in the 5'-untranslated region of the NOTCH2NLC gene on chromosome 1q21. ET6 has a material basis in heterozygous trinucleotide GGC repeat expansion in the 5'-untranslated region of the NOTCH2NLC gene on chromosome 1q21.

oculopharyngodistal myopathy (OPMD) is a type of myopathy that affects the muscles responsible for eye movement, facial movements, and swallowing. It causes progressive weakness in these muscles, which can lead to issues such as droopy eyelids (ptosis), difficulty moving the eyes (ophthalmoparesis), and problems with speech and swallowing. OPMD is a type of distal myopathy, which means it primarily affects the muscles in the arms, legs, and neck.
oculopharyngodistal myopathy 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy type 2 is a genetic disorder that affects muscle strength, particularly in the lower limbs and face. It's also known to cause ophthalmoplegia (problems with eye movements) in some cases. The condition is characterized by the expansion of trinucleotide repeats in the GIPC1 gene on chromosome 19p13, which leads to a shortage of functional phosphatase enzymes essential for muscle function. This results in weakness and atrophy of affected muscles. Oculopharyngodistal myopathy type 2 is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner, meaning that if one parent has the condition, there's a 50% chance that their child will inherit it.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 3 is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by progressive muscle weakness with ocular, facial, pharyngeal, and distal limb involvement, resulting in dysarthria and gait difficulties. It has a material basis in trinucleotide repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region (UTR) of the NOTCH2NLC gene on chromosome 1q21.

Oculopharyngodistal myopathy 4 is a type of autosomal dominant disease characterized by progressive ptosis, ophthalmoparesis, facial and masseter weakness, and muscle weakness of the distal limbs. It has material basis in trinucleotide repeat expansion (CGG) in the 5-prime untranslated region (UTR) of the RILPL1 gene on chromosome 12q24.

Intellectual Developmental Disorder with Ocular Anomalies and Distinctive Facial Features (IDDOF) is a type of syndromic intellectual disability. It is characterized by global developmental delay, mildly impaired intellectual development, ophthalmologic anomalies, microcephaly or relative microcephaly, hearing loss, and characteristic facial features, and has a genetic basis in heterozygous mutations in the MTSS2 gene on chromosome 16q22. It is also known by its exact synonyms IDDOF and MTSS2-related neurodevelopmental disorder.

Diffuse leptomeningeal glioneuronal tumor is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm. It is characterized by the presence of clear glial neoplastic cells reminiscent of oligodendroglioma. Another name for this condition is Diffuse leptomeningeal glioneuronal tumour.

Multinodular and vacuolating neuronal tumor is a type of central nervous system benign neoplasm that is composed of cells with glial and/or neuronal differentiation, forming multiple nodules with prominent vacuolation and affecting the cerebral hemispheres.

That is correct! A high-grade astrocytoma with piloid features is a type of anaplastic astrocytoma, and it is characterized by high-grade piloid and/or glioblastoma-like histological features. It can occur anywhere in the central nervous system but most often arises in the posterior fossa. Is there anything else I can help you with?

Polymorphous low-grade neuroepithelial tumour (PLGN) of the young, also known as polymorphous low-grade glioma, is a benign brain tumor that affects children and adolescents. It is characterized by its slow growth rate and the presence of oligodendroglial cells in the tumor tissue. PLGN can cause seizures and refractory epilepsy in some cases, which makes it essential to diagnose and treat this condition as early as possible. Surgical resection is often the primary treatment option for PLGN, followed by postoperative radiation therapy and/or chemotherapy depending on the tumor's location, size, and histological subtype.

Spindle cell oncocytoma is a type of tumor that affects the pituitary gland, which is located at the base of the brain. It is a benign (non-cancerous) tumor that is made up of spindle cells, which are a type of immature nerve cell found in the pituitary gland. Spindle cell oncocytoma typically grows slowly and does not spread to other parts of the body. It can cause symptoms such as headache, vision problems, and excessive production of certain hormones by the pituitary gland. Treatment options for spindle cell oncocytoma may include surgery, radiation therapy, or medications to control hormone production.

Lymphomatoid granulomatosis is a type of lymphoproliferative syndrome that can cause the overproduction (proliferation) of white blood cells called lymphocytes. These abnormal cells can infiltrate and accumulate within tissues, causing damage or destruction to the blood vessels within these tissues. It is important for those affected by this condition to seek medical attention and follow proper treatment plans to manage their symptoms effectively.
Grade I Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis is a type of lymphoid infiltrate that lacks large lymphocytes and has EBV-positive cells infrequently seen by in situ hybridization.

Grade II Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis is a type of Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis. It can be defined as a Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis that features the presence of occasional large lymphoid cells or immunoblasts in a polymorphous background, with more necrosis present than in Grade I Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis. Additionally, it can be identified through in situ hybridization, which shows EBV-positive cells readily seen.

Grade III Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis is a type of Lymphomatoid Granulomatosis. It has the definition of being characterized by the presence of aggregates of neoplastic large B-lymphocytes, usually admixed with pleomorphic and Hodgkin-like cells, in a background of chronic inflammation. Necrotic changes are present and are usually extensive.

That is correct. Intravascular large B-cell lymphoma is a subtype of B-cell lymphoma that is characterized by the presence of malignant B cells exclusively in the lumina of small vessels, particularly capillaries. It is also known as primary intravascular lymphoma or lymphomatoid granulomas. These tumors are rare and tend to be aggressive, with a poor prognosis. Treatment options for intravascular large B-cell lymphoma may include chemotherapy, immunotherapy, or targeted therapy, depending on the specific characteristics of the disease and the patient's overall health.

T cell non Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of cancer that affects the T cells, which are a type of white blood cell. It is part of a larger group of cancers called non-Hodgkin lymphomas, which affect the lymphatic system. The lymphatic system is a network of vessels and organs that helps protect the body against infection and disease. T cell non Hodgkin lymphoma can occur at any age but is more common in people over 60 years old. It is usually treated with chemotherapy, radiation therapy, or a combination of both.

Primary Diffuse Large B Cell Lymphoma of the Central Nervous System (PLBCCL) is a type of diffuse large B cell lymphoma that originates in the central nervous system. It is characterized by the presence of large, neoplastic cells with immature features and is typically associated with high levels of serum lactate dehydrogenase (LDH). PLBCCL can present with a range of symptoms, including headache, nausea, vomiting, and seizures, as well as weakness, numbness or tingling in the extremities. Diagnosis is typically made through imaging studies such as MRI, biopsy, and cerebrospinal fluid analysis. Treatment options for PLBCCL include chemotherapy, radiation therapy, and stem cell transplantation.

Extraventricular neurocytoma is a type of cerebral ventricle cancer. It is characterized by the presence of neoplastic uniform, round cells with neuronal differentiation that arises from the brain parenchyma. This type of tumor does not involve the lateral ventricles.

Central nervous system tumor with BCR-ABL1 internal tandem duplication is a type of central nervous system embryonal tumor.
Central nervous system tumor with BCR-ABL1 internal tandem duplication has definition A central nervous system embryonal tumor that is characterized by the presence of uniform oval or spindle-shaped cells with round or oval nuclei, pseudorosette formation, and a t(4;11)(q28;q23) translocation leading to BCR-ABL1 fusion gene..
Central nervous system tumor with BCR-ABL1 internal tandem duplication has exact synonym CNS tumour with BCR-ABL1 internal tandem duplication.

Primary intracranial sarcoma Dicer1 mutant is a type of brain sarcoma characterized by the presence of malignant pleomorphic or spindle neoplastic cells, which demonstrate myogenic and/or chondroid differentiation. This condition is often associated with mutations in the DICER1 gene.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 1 (MSS1) is a genetic disorder characterized by multiple joint fusions, conductive deafness, and specific facial features. It is caused by mutations in the Noggin gene located on chromosome 17q22.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 2, also known as MSS2, is a rare genetic disorder that affects the skeletal system and causes progressive joint fusions. It is characterized by the fusion of multiple bones in various parts of the body such as fingers, wrists, ankles, and the cervical spine. Additionally, people with MSS2 may have a distinct facial appearance, including a broad hemicylindrical nose, and progressive conductive hearing loss. The disorder is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern, which means that a single copy of the faulty gene is sufficient to cause the condition. The gene responsible for MSS2 is called GDF5 and is located on chromosome 20q11.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 3, also known as MSS 3, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by multiple joint fusions in the hands, conductive deafness, and specific facial features such as a broad, tubular-shaped nose, and a thin upper vermilion. It has a material basis in a heterozygous mutation in the FGF9 gene on chromosome 13q12.

Multiple synostoses syndrome 4 (MSS4) is a genetic disorder that affects the development of bones in the hands and feet. It is caused by mutations in the GDF6 gene, which is located on chromosome 8q22. The condition is characterized by fusion of the carpal and tarsal bones, as well as conductive hearing loss.
contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome 1a is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Contractures pterygia and spondylocarpotarsal fusion syndrome 1b, also known as autosomal recessive multiple pterygium syndrome, is a genetic disorder that affects the joints, skin, and bones. It is caused by mutations in the MYH3 gene on chromosome 17p13. The condition is characterized by contractures of proximal and distal joints, pterygia involving the neck, elbows, fingers, and/or knees, and variable vertebral, carpal, and tarsal fusions. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the mutated gene, one from each parent, to develop the condition.

Breast Implant Illness (BII) is a term that refers to a collection of symptoms and medical conditions that have been reported by some women who have received breast implants. It is not currently recognized as an official medical diagnosis, but it has gained attention in recent years due to the number of reports from patients experiencing various health issues after getting breast implants.
While there are many different symptoms that have been linked to BII, the most commonly reported ones include fatigue, problems with memory or concentration, joint and muscle pain, hair loss, weight changes, and anxiety/depression. However, it's important to note that not all women who receive breast implants will experience any of these symptoms, and many other factors can contribute to these types of issues.
It is recommended that anyone considering breast augmentation should carefully weigh the risks and benefits, and consult with their healthcare provider to discuss their options thoroughly before making a decision. Additionally, if you have received breast implants and are experiencing any concerning symptoms or health problems, it's crucial to seek medical advice from a qualified healthcare professional who can evaluate your individual case and provide appropriate care and treatment as needed.

Neurodevelopmental disorder with poor growth, spastic tetraplegia, and hearing loss is a type of autosomal recessive intellectual developmental disorder. It is characterized by poor growth, spastic tetraplegia, and hearing loss, and has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the PSMC1 gene on chromosome 14q32. This condition has been given the exact synonym NEDGTH.

developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 94 is a type of developmental and epileptic encephalopathy.
developmental and epileptic encephalopathy 94 has definition A developmental and epileptic encephalopathy characterized by onset of multiple seizure types in the first few years of life and associated with poor prognosis and that has_material_basis_in heterozygous mutation in the CHD2 gene on chromosome 15q26..

oxoglutarate dehydrogenase deficiency is a metabolic disorder that affects the body's ability to convert a compound called alpha-ketoglutarate into another compound called glutamate. This disruption in the normal metabolic pathway can lead to various symptoms, including infantile and pediatric onset basal ganglia-associated movement disorders, hypotonia, developmental delays, ataxia, and seizures. It is caused by a mutation in the oxoglutarate dehydrogenase gene (OGDH) located on chromosome 7p13. This condition can be inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that an individual must inherit two copies of the mutated gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder.

That is correct. Neurodevelopmental disorder with regression abnormal movements loss of speech and seizures, also known as NEDAMSS, is a type of neurodegenerative disease that is characterized by neurodevelopmental regression that became apparent between 2 and 10 years of age after normal early development in most patients. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the IRF2BPL gene on chromosome 14q24.

Familial hyperinsulinemic hypoglycemia 8 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, characterized by protein-related hypoglycemia and persistent mild hyperammonemia. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the SLC25A36 gene on chromosome 3q23.

Glycogen storage disease type I, also known as von Gierke's disease, is a genetic disorder characterized by the accumulation of glycogen in various tissues, including the liver, muscles, and brain. This leads to severe hypoglycemia (low blood sugar levels) and hepatomegaly (enlarged liver), as well as other symptoms such as growth retardation, delayed puberty, lactic acidosis, hyperlipidemia (elevated levels of fats in the blood), and hyperuricemia (high uric acid levels). Affected individuals often have a high incidence of hepatic adenomas (benign tumors of the liver) and an increased risk of developing certain types of cancer. Treatment options for this condition include dietary modifications, enzyme replacement therapy, and regular monitoring of blood sugar levels to prevent hypoglycemia.<|end_of_text|>

Glycogen Storage Disease Type I (IB), also known as GSD I, is a genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to store and process glycogen. It is caused by mutations in the G6PT1 gene, which is located on chromosome 11q23. This condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive pattern, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) to develop the disorder. Symptoms of GSD I can include progressive short stature, muscle weakness, and abnormal fat deposits, among other things.

Glycogen storage disease type I is a rare genetic disorder that affects the body's ability to store and use glycogen, which is a form of sugar stored in the liver and muscles. It is caused by mutations in the G6PT1 gene, which encodes the glucose-6-phosphate translocase enzyme, located on chromosome 11q23. The disorder can present with symptoms such as progressive short stature, muscle weakness, and a triad of symptoms including malaise, increased respiratory effort, and increased echogenicity on chest imaging. Treatment is generally supportive and aimed at managing complications.

Progeria, also known as Hutchinson-Gilford syndrome, is a rare genetic condition characterized by premature aging. It is caused by a mutation in the LMNA gene, which encodes for an essential component of the nuclear envelope called lamin A. The resultant lack of functional lamin A leads to cellular dysfunction, including the breakdown of the nuclear envelope, and ultimately contributes to the premature aging of affected individuals. Symptoms include growth failure, premature aging, and an increased risk of certain age-related diseases such as atherosclerosis and cancer. Progeria is often fatal in early childhood, with an average life expectancy of around two years after diagnosis. There is no cure for progeria, but research is ongoing to better understand the condition and identify potential treatments.

Wiedemann-Rautenstrauch Syndrome (WRS) is a rare genetic disorder that affects infants, usually during the first three months of life. It is characterized by growth delays, poor muscle tone, and an aged appearance. WRS can also cause intellectual disabilities and other developmental issues. The syndrome is caused by mutations in the POLR3A gene on chromosome 10q22. It is considered a progeroid syndrome, which means it causes premature aging.

Nestor Guillermo Progeria Syndrome is a rare genetic condition that affects children. It causes lipoatrophy, osteoporosis, and severe osteolysis. The disease does not cause any cardiovascular impairment, diabetes mellitus or hypertriglyceridemia but it has a significant impact on the patient's quality of life due to the profound skeletal abnormalities caused by homozygous mutation in the BANF1 gene located on chromosome 11q13. Onset occurs after two years of age. The condition is considered as a progeroid syndrome, which means it has similar characteristics to premature aging.

Becker disease is a type of myotonia congenita, characterized by muscle stiffness and an inability to relax after voluntary contraction. It has a material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the gene encoding skeletal muscle chloride channel-1 (CLCN1) on chromosome 7q34.

Thomsen disease is a type of myotonia congenita, which is characterized by muscle stiffness and an inability of the muscle to relax after voluntary contraction. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the gene encoding skeletal muscle chloride channel-1 (CLCN1) on chromosome 7q34, and it is inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. The disease has been referred to as Congenital myotonia, autosomal dominant form, and Thomsen's disease.

Congenital myopathy is a type of muscle disease that is present at birth. It is characterized by muscle weakness and hypotonia, which means low muscle tone. There are many different types of congenital myopathies, each with its own set of symptoms and causes. Some common symptoms include poor muscle tone, weakness, and difficulty moving or walking. In some cases, congenital myopathy can also affect the heart and other organs. Treatment for congenital myopathy depends on the specific type and severity of the disease, but may include physical therapy, medication, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs or walking aids.

Myofibrillar myopathy 11, also known as MFN2 myopathy, is a type of congenital myopathy that affects the muscles. It typically presents with slowly progressive proximal muscle weakness in the first decade of life, and has been linked to mutations in the UNC45B gene on chromosome 17q11.
Congenital myopathy 2B is a type of autosomal recessive disease.

Congenital myopathy 2c is a type of autosomal dominant disease.
Congenital myopathy 2c is a type of congenital myopathy.
Congenital myopathy 2c is a type of something that at least has material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance.
Congenital myopathy 2c has definition: A congenital myopathy characterized by severe congenital weakness usually resulting in death from respiratory failure in the first year or so of life, and that has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ACTA1 gene on chromosome 1q42. Heterozygous mutation in the ACTA1 gene can also cause autosomal dominant typical congenital myopathy-2A (CMYP2A). Biallelic mutation in the ACTA1 gene causes autosomal recessive severe infantile congenital myopathy-2B (CMYP2B).

Congenital myopathy 5, also known as Salih myopathy, is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects muscle strength. It typically presents in infancy with symptoms such as neonatal hypotonia (low muscle tone), delayed motor development, and often includes distal contractures. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the gene encoding titin, which is located on chromosome 2q31. It is also known by the synonym congenital myopathy-5 with cardiomyopathy.

Congenital myopathy 8, also known as congenital distal myopathy with hypotonia and developmental delay, is a type of autosomal dominant disease. It is characterized by hypotonia (low muscle tone) and delayed motor development, which can lead to difficulties walking or loss of ambulation within the first few decades. The condition has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the ACTN2 gene on chromosome 1q43. Heterozygous mutation in the same gene also causes distal myopathy-6 (MPD6), which has a later onset and is less severe.

Congenital myopathy 9a is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects the muscles and causes weakness. It is characterized by neonatal hypotonia, poor feeding, fractures of the long bones, and respiratory insufficiency. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the FXR1 gene on chromosome 3q28.

Congenital myopathy 9b, also known as CMYP9A, is a type of autosomal recessive congenital myopathy characterized by neonatal hypotonia (decreased muscle tone), followed by mildly delayed walking in childhood, mainly affecting proximal muscles. It has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the FXR1 gene on chromosome 3q28. Biallelic mutation in the FXR1 gene also causes CMYP9A.

Congenital myopathy 10b is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects muscle strength and causes various symptoms such as infantile- or childhood-onset myopathy, areflexia, dysphagia, and respiratory distress. It is caused by mutations in the MEGF10 gene on chromosome 5q23.

Congenital myopathy 14, also known as myotubular myopathy, is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by severe muscle weakness that is present at birth or sometimes in utero. The condition has a material basis in homozygous mutations in the MYL1 gene on chromosome 2q32. Affected infants often have difficulty breathing independently and require mechanical ventilation for varying lengths of time.

Congenital myopathy 15, also known as nemaline myopathy type 15, is a genetic disorder characterized by muscle weakness and low tone. It is caused by mutations in the TNNC2 gene, which is located on chromosome 20q13. The condition typically presents shortly after birth with severe respiratory insufficiency and feeding difficulties, requiring mechanical ventilation or tube feeding.

Congenital myopathy 16 is a type of autosomal dominant disease. This means that it can be inherited from one parent, and there's an increased chance for the disease to be passed on to future generations. The exact cause of congenital myopathy 16 is not entirely understood but it appears to have a genetic basis. It's characterized by onset of hypotonia (low muscle tone) and tremor in infancy, mildly delayed walking, unsteady gait, proximal muscle weakness, and high-frequency tremor of the limbs.

Congenital Myopathy 17 is a type of autosomal recessive disease. It is characterized by hypotonia and respiratory insufficiency present at birth, along with an associated high diaphragmatic dome on imaging. The condition has a material basis in homozygous mutation in the MYOD1 gene on chromosome 11p15.
Congenital myopathy 18 is a type of autosomal dominant disease.

Congenital myopathy 19, also known as Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease type 1A, is a genetic disorder characterized by muscle weakness and atrophy. It typically affects the voluntary muscles of the arms, legs, feet, and face, leading to difficulties with walking and other motor skills. Scoliosis, or abnormal curvature of the spine, may also occur in some cases. The condition is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, which means that a person must inherit two copies of the gene (one from each parent) for the disorder to develop. It's caused by mutations in the PAX7 gene on chromosome 1p36.

Congenital Myopathy 20 (CM-20) is a type of autosomal recessive disease.
CM-20 is a form of congenital myopathy.
CM-20 has material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance.
CM-20 has been defined as a congenital myopathy that has_material_basis_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the RYR3 gene on chromosome 15q13 and shows wide phenotypic variability.
Some patients with CM-20 present early in life, typically in childhood, with proximal muscle weakness affecting the lower and upper limbs, making it difficult to run or climb. Others may be diagnosed soon after birth with congenital limb or distal contractures.
congenital myopathy 21 is a type of autosomal recessive congenital myopathy characterized by diaphragmatic weakness and spinal rigidity resulting from mutations in the DNAJB4 gene on chromosome 1p31.

Congenital myopathy 22a is a type of congenital myopathy characterized by onset of muscle weakness in utero or soon after birth and having_material\_basis\_in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the SCN4A gene on chromosome 17q23. Biallelic mutation in the SCN4A gene also causes severe fetal congenital myopathy 22B..

Congenital myopathy 22B is a type of autosomal recessive disease that affects muscle strength and movement. It is characterized by severe muscle weakness in utero, as seen in fetal akinesia, and can be caused by mutations in the SCN4A gene on chromosome 17q23.

Spinal muscular atrophy, also known as SMA, is a genetic disorder that affects the nerve cells in the spinal cord. It causes muscle weakness and atrophy (wasting). There are different types of SMA, including Jokela type. This type is characterized by adult-onset of muscle cramps and fasciculations affecting the proximal and distal muscles of the upper and lower limbs. It has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CHCHD10 gene on chromosome 22q11.

Isolated mitochondrial myopathy is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means that it can be passed down through generations in families. It is characterized by onset of proximal lower limb weakness and exercise intolerance in the first decade of life, and has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the CHCHD10 gene on chromosome 22q11.

Epidermolytic hyperkeratosis 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease, which means it can be passed down through family genes. This condition causes an excessive buildup of skin cells and can lead to thickened, scaly patches on the skin. It usually presents in childhood with erythema and blistering, but can also affect adults. The condition has a material basis in mutations in the KRT1 gene on chromosome 12q13.

epidermolytic hyperkeratosis 2 is a type of epidermolytic hyperkeratosis.
epidermolytic hyperkeratosis 2 has the definition An epidermolytic hyperkeratosis characterized by generalized erythema, erosions, scaling, and easily breaking blisters that become less frequent later in life, while hyperkeratosis increases and that has_material_basis_in heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the keratin-10 gene (KRT10) on chromosome 17q21..

Spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy 2, also known as SQCP-2 or KANK1-related spastic quadriplegia with cerebellar ataxia, is a rare genetic disorder characterized by the loss of motor function and coordination due to mutations in the KANK1 gene. It is inherited in an autosomal recessive manner, meaning that both copies of the gene must be affected for the condition to develop.
Symptoms typically appear during infancy or early childhood and may include difficulty walking, muscle stiffness, tremors, and problems with balance and coordination. Seizures may also occur in some individuals. As the condition progresses, it can lead to significant disability and affect quality of life.
Currently, there is no cure for SQCP-2, but treatment options are available to manage symptoms and improve function. These may include physical therapy, speech therapy, medications to control seizures or muscle spasms, and assistive devices such as wheelchairs and walkers.

Spastic quadriplegic cerebral palsy type 3 (CPSQ3) is a form of autosomal recessive disease that affects the muscular and motor functions of an individual. It is caused by mutations in the ADD3 gene on chromosome 10q24. The condition results in spasticity, weakness, and difficulties with movement and coordination. There are no specific treatments for this form of cerebral palsy, but management strategies can help improve quality of life.

Pierpont syndrome is a rare genetic disorder that affects a person's physical and intellectual development. It is caused by a mutation in the TBL1XR1 gene, which is located on chromosome 3q26. The main features of Pierpont syndrome include distinctive facial characteristics such as an underbite, plantar fat pads, and other limb anomalies. Additionally, affected individuals may experience developmental delays or intellectual disabilities. It's important to note that not all cases of Pierpont syndrome will have all these features, but they are common in most cases.

Distal myopathy with rimmed vacuoles is a type of autosomal dominant disease that affects the distal upper and lower limbs, leading to walking difficulties. It is characterized by adult onset muscle weakness, proximal weakness of the shoulder girdle muscles, and has a material basis in heterozygous mutation in the SQSTM1 gene on chromosome 5q35.

That is correct. Neurodegeneration with ataxia, dystonia, and gaze palsy (childhood onset) is a type of neurodegenerative disease that affects children and adolescents. It is characterized by the onset of gait ataxia, cognitive decline, and gaze palsy in the first or second decades of life. This condition has a genetic basis, specifically due to homozygous mutation in the SQSTM1 gene located on chromosome 5q35. It is important for healthcare providers to recognize this condition early and provide appropriate treatment and support to affected individuals and their families.

Paget's disease of bone, also known as Paget's disease, is a type of bone disorder characterized by increased bone turnover, leading to the weakening and deformation of bones. It can affect any bone in the body but is most commonly found in the pelvis, legs, and arms. The exact cause of Paget's disease is unknown, but it may be related to age, genetics, or certain medical conditions such as hyperparathyroidism and vitamin D deficiency. Treatment for Paget's disease typically includes medications to slow down bone turnover, calcium supplements to prevent osteoporosis, and in some cases, surgery to repair or replace damaged bones.

Paget's disease of bone 3, also known as Paget's disease of bone type 3 or Paget disease of bone-3, is a specific form of the condition that is characterized by the presence of mutations in the SQSTM1 gene on chromosome 5q35. This genetic mutation leads to abnormalities in the regulation of bone remodeling and can result in bone deformities, pain, and other skeletal issues.

It is important to note that Paget's disease of bone 3 is one of several types of the condition, with each type being characterized by specific genetic mutations or changes in gene expression. The exact cause of Paget's disease is not fully understood, but it is believed to involve a combination of environmental and genetic factors that contribute to its development.

In some cases, Paget's disease may be associated with certain medications or medical conditions, such as hyperparathyroidism, vitamin D deficiency, or rheumatoid arthritis. However, the underlying cause of each case of Paget's disease will depend on a variety of individual factors and may require a comprehensive evaluation by a healthcare provider to determine.

Treatment options for Paget's disease typically aim to alleviate symptoms and manage complications associated with the condition, such as bone pain or deformities. This may include medications to reduce inflammation, bisphosphonates to slow down bone loss, and calcium supplements to maintain healthy levels of this mineral in the blood. In some cases, surgery may also be necessary to address severe deformities or other complications associated with Paget's disease.

Paget's disease of bone 4, also known as Paget disease of bone-4, is a type of autosomal dominant disorder. It is part of the broader category of Paget's diseases of bone, which are characterized by increased bone turnover and the deposition of abnormal bone tissue in the affected skeletal sites.
Paget's disease of bone 4 specifically affects the fourth metatarsal, which is located on the outer side of the foot, between the second and third toes. The condition causes the bones to be larger and thicker than normal due to the excessive deposition of bone tissue in that particular area.
The inheritance pattern for Paget's disease of bone 4 is autosomal dominant, meaning that a single copy of the gene responsible for the disorder (located on chromosome 5) is sufficient to cause the condition in affected individuals. The risk of developing Paget's disease of bone 4 increases if a family member has the disorder.
There is no known cure for Paget's disease of bone 4, but treatment options are available to manage symptoms and improve quality of life. These may include medications such as bisphosphonates or calcitonin to reduce inflammation and slow down bone turnover, as well as lifestyle changes like weight loss and regular exercise to maintain overall health and prevent further bone loss.
